# Go Code Gate

The user controls when implementation starts. **Do not make changes until they say the exact trigger phrase: `go code`.**

## Before `go code`

- **No implementation** — no file edits, creates, deletes, refactors, or config changes (even one line)
- **No execution that changes the project** — no installs, migrations, commits, pushes, or builds run to implement a task
- **Allowed** — read/search the codebase, answer questions, plan, review, queue tasks, clarify requirements
- **Multi-prompt batches** — collect all prompts the user sends; execute them **in order** only after `go code`
- **Start of each session** — briefly confirm the gate is active (one line is enough): e.g. *"Holding until you say go code."*

## When the user says `go code`

- Execute queued work **one prompt after another**, in the order received
- Apply the same gate to **every** change, including single-line fixes — no exceptions unless the user explicitly says otherwise in that message

## After work completes

- Resume holding until the next `go code` for any further implementation

## Examples

**User:** "Fix the typo in `brain.ts` line 13."  
→ Acknowledge and hold. Do not edit.

**User:** "Also add a test."  
→ Add to queue. Still hold.

**User:** "go code"  
→ Fix typo, then add test, in order.

**User:** "go code — just the typo"  
→ Only the typo; ignore earlier queued items unless they restate them.
